lead_paragraph: In early 2007, a senior salesman on the emerging-markets desk at a major U.S. investment bank — one that subsequently escaped perdition by grasping a lifeline from another institution — called me in a huff. I work at a hedge fund, running the group that makes loans and other investments in developing countries. “I’m really sorry,” the salesman said, his tone betraying annoyance rather than contrition, “but it’s gotten to the point that we can’t show you deals anymore. You guys are too difficult.” I was puzzled. What had we done? “You’re too negative! All you do is ask pointed questions! And in the end, you pass.” Our sin: instead of responding to each pitch with an enthusiastic yes, we asked for more data. And sometimes — maybe even more than half the time! — we said no. The last straw was apparently that we’d turned down a gas project in Indonesia; a few questions revealed it to be controlled by a shady family that defaulted on lenders a few years before, sticking them with losses of 90 cents on the dollar. Details!

They managed to pay for health insurance out of pocket for six months, until the premiums jumped to $832 a month. Sheila, who was forced to quit chemotherapy midtreatment, is tempting the odds.

abstract: Granted, 3,374 miles is a long way to go for a drink. And the trip was not easy: a red-eye to Heathrow, a flight to Glasgow, a drive through the wind-swept Scottish highlands and a bone-rattling pontoon boat ride. But we finally reached our destination, the island of Sanda in the North Sea. As we drew near, we saw mountainous green hills and a half-moon bay with a handful of stone cottages, including a tavern claiming to be the remotest pub in the United Kingdom. But it wasn't the remoteness that attracted us. It was the name. The moment we heard of the tavern some eight months before, we knew we had to come.. . .But I'm getting ahead of myself.

lead_paragraph: Trash had been piling up in colorful, rotting drifts for more than three weeks when I arrived in Baghdad in April. On my first day as an interpreter for the Office of Reconstruction and Humanitarian Assistance (ORHA), I helped Franz Froelicher negotiate the city's trash contract. Franz, a Swiss-American geochemist with the Army Corps of Engineers, had cleaned up after hurricanes in Puerto Rico, Colombia and Honduras. He knew exactly what he wanted in Baghdad: a flat rate for every cubic meter of trash delivered to the landfill. He would have to rely on contractors and dump trucks to dig the city out.
